&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:23.570 --> 00:00:25.030
&gt;&gt; Denise Woltering-Vargas:
Good afternoon.

00:00:25.030 --> 00:00:28.070
I'd like to start, I know
we're running a little behind.

00:00:28.070 --> 00:00:30.360
My name is Denise
Woltering-Vargas.

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:33.410
I am the Program Manager
at Tulane University Center

00:00:33.410 --> 00:00:34.950
for Latin American Studies.

00:00:34.950 --> 00:00:37.260
Thank you.

00:00:37.260 --> 00:00:41.970
And I've been working with
the Americas Awards since 2011

00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:46.440
with Julie Kline, the
founder's supervision guidance

00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:47.760
and direction.

00:00:47.760 --> 00:00:49.730
She's been very helpful
in helping me

00:00:49.730 --> 00:00:55.090
to program our program here
in D.C. I'd like to say thanks

00:00:55.090 --> 00:00:58.950
to Pamela Jackson at the Center
for the Book and Georgette Dorn

00:00:58.950 --> 00:01:00.850
from the Hispanic Division.

00:01:00.850 --> 00:01:04.970
Good afternoon and welcome
to the 2016 Americas Award.

00:01:04.970 --> 00:01:09.300
On behalf of the Consortium of
Latin American Studies Programs,

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:12.540
myself at Tulane and Lisa
Finelli at Vanderbilt,

00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:14.990
we welcome you to
today's ceremony.

00:01:14.990 --> 00:01:19.600
The Americas Award was
founded in 1993 by Julie Kline

00:01:19.600 --> 00:01:21.940
at the Center for Latin
America and Caribbean Studies

00:01:21.940 --> 00:01:24.890
at the University of
Wisconsin in Milwaukee.

00:01:24.890 --> 00:01:29.070
This award is one of the most
important programs of CLASP.

00:01:29.070 --> 00:01:33.980
It is where we get the most
impact outreach out of teaching

00:01:33.980 --> 00:01:36.730
and engaging about Latin
America within the community

00:01:36.730 --> 00:01:38.780
and within classrooms.

00:01:38.780 --> 00:01:42.840
Awards are given up to two
books each year and are selected

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:44.970
for their distinctive
literary quality,

00:01:44.970 --> 00:01:49.320
cultural contextualization,
exceptional integration of text,

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:53.100
illustration and design and
potential for classroom use.

00:01:53.100 --> 00:01:55.320
And that is an important
part to us.

00:01:55.320 --> 00:01:59.130
Its ability to be used in
classrooms and teaching.

00:01:59.130 --> 00:02:01.280
The goal of the award
is to link the Americas

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:04.580
to reach beyond geographic
borders, focusing, instead,

00:02:04.580 --> 00:02:08.090
on cultural heritages
within the hemisphere.

00:02:08.090 --> 00:02:12.420
The committee, this year we
had an excellent committee.

00:02:12.420 --> 00:02:14.740
Some of the committee
members are here.

00:02:14.740 --> 00:02:17.120
The Americas Award review
committee was comprised this

00:02:17.120 --> 00:02:20.160
year of teachers, community
activists and librarians

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:24.030
from Tennessee, North
Carolina, Wisconsin, New Mexico

00:02:24.030 --> 00:02:27.320
and right here in
Washington D.C. In the fall,

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:29.260
the books are submitted,
and beginning in Mach,

00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:32.640
the committee gathers via
Skype and Google Hangout

00:02:32.640 --> 00:02:37.110
and other alternative conference
calls in a series of meetings

00:02:37.110 --> 00:02:39.580
to make very important
decisions.

00:02:39.580 --> 00:02:42.690
These conversations are
enlightening, insightful

00:02:42.690 --> 00:02:45.780
and at times very spirited
and show the passion

00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:47.080
that the committee members feel

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:49.810
about the diverse
cultures of Latin America.

00:02:49.810 --> 00:02:52.520
Lisa and I are extremely
grateful for the hard work

00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:54.090
of the committee and
the care that they put

00:02:54.090 --> 00:02:56.880
into choosing the
award each year.

00:02:56.880 --> 00:02:59.080
We would like to say
a special gracias

00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:00.880
to Kyra Phillips Shnore
[phonetic] at the University

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:03.530
of New Mexico for her
extra help this year.

00:03:03.530 --> 00:03:07.250
Stepping in to help coordinate
committee conversations.

00:03:07.250 --> 00:03:09.700
A unique element of the
Americas Award, as I mentioned,

00:03:09.700 --> 00:03:12.770
is the ability to be
used in K12 classrooms.

00:03:12.770 --> 00:03:16.050
The award emphasizes the
potential for classroom use.

00:03:16.050 --> 00:03:20.520
So as you see the books cycling
behind me, you'll see snippets

00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:24.940
of committee members' opinions,
thoughts, ideas and ways

00:03:24.940 --> 00:03:28.890
that they see this award being
incorporated into the classroom,

00:03:28.890 --> 00:03:33.220
as well as recommended
grade levels.

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:36.140
Educators have developed and
continued to develop pre-K

00:03:36.140 --> 00:03:39.330
through 12 curricula to
be used with each book.

00:03:39.330 --> 00:03:41.450
If you're interested in
learning about these resources

00:03:41.450 --> 00:03:43.870
and participating in other
opportunities that we have,

00:03:43.870 --> 00:03:47.770
please visit on our
website claspprograms.org.

00:03:47.770 --> 00:03:51.360
It's on the end of
this screen slideshow.

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:54.230
And this year's program features
a special educator workshop

00:03:54.230 --> 00:03:57.090
tonight, this evening, across
the street from Busboys

00:03:57.090 --> 00:03:58.410
and Poets at Mulebone.

00:03:58.410 --> 00:04:03.050
We'll have a teacher workshop
highlighting this year's award

00:04:03.050 --> 00:04:06.680
winner, Ashley Hope
Perez and Alma Flor Ada.

00:04:06.680 --> 00:04:08.340
So please join us.

00:04:08.340 --> 00:04:09.810
I'd like to hand it over to one

00:04:09.810 --> 00:04:12.110
of our committee
members, Paula Mason.

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:23.110
&gt;&gt; Paula Mason: Hello everyone.

00:04:23.110 --> 00:04:25.860
My name is Paula Mason, and
I'm a review committee member

00:04:25.860 --> 00:04:28.390
for the Americas Award
and a public librarian

00:04:28.390 --> 00:04:30.200
from the Milwaukee area.

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:33.260
As a librarian, I find that one
of the most valuable aspects

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:36.750
of this award is the annotated
bibliography that we create

00:04:36.750 --> 00:04:38.740
of commended and
honor book titles,

00:04:38.740 --> 00:04:41.380
along with our two
award winners.

00:04:41.380 --> 00:04:44.730
You'll find all these titles
listed in our program book

00:04:44.730 --> 00:04:46.870
and showing on the screens.

00:04:46.870 --> 00:04:51.240
To highlight just a few of
these suburb commended titles,

00:04:51.240 --> 00:04:55.240
I'm going to just discuss just
a few of the themes that we saw.

00:04:55.240 --> 00:04:58.670
So, several of them touched on
important and relevant topics,

00:04:58.670 --> 00:05:01.110
such as breaking down
barriers in our community

00:05:01.110 --> 00:05:03.090
and dispelling stereotypes.

00:05:03.090 --> 00:05:06.370
Books such as the young adult's
debut from Marie Marquardt,

00:05:06.370 --> 00:05:10.450
Dream Things True and Cynthia
Lord's A Handful of Stars,

00:05:10.450 --> 00:05:14.330
do an excellent job of giving
characters, giving us characters

00:05:14.330 --> 00:05:17.550
that bridge divisions
in their communities.

00:05:17.550 --> 00:05:21.810
Also, Margarita Engle gave us
two fantastic books this year,

00:05:21.810 --> 00:05:24.140
The Picture Book,
Dream Drum Girl:

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:28.390
How One Girl's Courage Changed
Music and her child memoir,

00:05:28.390 --> 00:05:31.510
Enchanted Air: Two
Cultures, Two Wings.

00:05:31.510 --> 00:05:34.910
In Dream Drum Girl,
illustrated by Rafael Lopez,

00:05:34.910 --> 00:05:39.200
we witness Cuban musician,
Millo Castro Zaldarriaga desired

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:42.520
to play the bongo drums,
traditionally an instrument

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:44.700
that only boys could play.

00:05:44.700 --> 00:05:47.230
We learn that in courageously
breaking this stereotype,

00:05:47.230 --> 00:05:50.290
she went on to become a
celebrated world-famous musician

00:05:50.290 --> 00:05:51.860
in her own right.

00:05:51.860 --> 00:05:53.160
In all of these books,

00:05:53.160 --> 00:05:56.760
we see characters confront
seemingly impossible challenges

00:05:56.760 --> 00:05:58.820
and find creative solutions.

00:05:58.820 --> 00:06:01.540
And in this way, as
readers, we can begin

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:03.850
to soar alongside them too.

00:06:03.850 --> 00:06:05.840
We're also honored today
to be in the presence

00:06:05.840 --> 00:06:08.520
of Alma Flor Ada, the
award-winning author

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:11.390
of many titles and a prevailing
authority on bilingual

00:06:11.390 --> 00:06:13.630
and multicultural education.

00:06:13.630 --> 00:06:17.470
In her gem of a book, Island
Treasures: Growing up in Cuba,

00:06:17.470 --> 00:06:20.970
the reader can delight in
her many family stories

00:06:20.970 --> 00:06:24.520
from her childhood, which
offer beautiful lessons.

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:27.740
Filled with dozens of personal
photos and illustrations,

00:06:27.740 --> 00:06:30.640
this book feels like a
special and intimate journey

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:33.990
through precious family
heirlooms and stories,

00:06:33.990 --> 00:06:36.470
which is very fitting
considering the generous

00:06:36.470 --> 00:06:39.970
and open nature of her family
as described in the book.

00:06:39.970 --> 00:06:43.970
We also saw similar themes
of inner generational wisdom

00:06:43.970 --> 00:06:47.400
and the importance of passing
along family memories in books

00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:51.330
such as My Tata's Remedies,
Los remedios de mi tata

00:06:51.330 --> 00:06:56.260
by Roni Capin Rivera-Ashford,
illustrated by Antonio Castro L.

00:06:56.260 --> 00:06:59.930
and Monica Brown in her
picture book Maya's Blanket,

00:06:59.930 --> 00:07:01.680
illustrated by David Diaz.

00:07:01.680 --> 00:07:05.130
These are just a few of
the many wonderful books

00:07:05.130 --> 00:07:08.600
that are officially recognized
as our commended titles.

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:10.920
I'm also very pleased to discuss

00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:13.430
with you our two
honored books today.

00:07:13.430 --> 00:07:15.870
Our first title is
Growing up Pedro:

00:07:15.870 --> 00:07:17.570
How the Martinez
Brothers Made it

00:07:17.570 --> 00:07:20.900
from the Dominican Republic all
the Way to the Major Leagues

00:07:20.900 --> 00:07:23.590
by author and illustrator
Matt Tavares.

00:07:23.590 --> 00:07:26.120
While there have been many
Dominican baseball players

00:07:26.120 --> 00:07:30.170
in the major leagues, none have
kindled the deep enthusiasm

00:07:30.170 --> 00:07:34.250
and allegiance and so many
fans as pitcher Pedro Martinez.

00:07:34.250 --> 00:07:37.810
In his nonfiction picture book
geared for elementary students,

00:07:37.810 --> 00:07:40.790
Tavares celebrates this
larger-than-life baseball hero

00:07:40.790 --> 00:07:44.270
with incredibly realistic
paintings and simple text.

00:07:44.270 --> 00:07:46.970
We're transported to the
world of the Martinez brothers

00:07:46.970 --> 00:07:48.270
as they made their way

00:07:48.270 --> 00:07:49.820
from a poor Dominican
village all the way

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:51.920
to the US Major Leagues.

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:54.670
The relationship between the
two brothers is the centerpiece

00:07:54.670 --> 00:07:58.200
of the book, whether throwing
rocks at mangos as young boys

00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:01.520
to practice their aim or
pitching against each other

00:08:01.520 --> 00:08:04.290
in an historic game in 1996,

00:08:04.290 --> 00:08:07.070
Pedro and Ramone maintain
their deep connection

00:08:07.070 --> 00:08:09.890
and give each other the
strength they need to continue

00:08:09.890 --> 00:08:12.020
through times of difficulties.

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:15.050
Without his older brother,
Ramone, Tavares leads us

00:08:15.050 --> 00:08:16.800
to believe there
would be no Pedro

00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:19.380
on the same national stage.

00:08:19.380 --> 00:08:21.920
From a small boy watching
his big brother play

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:25.350
in their village
as a star pitcher,

00:08:25.350 --> 00:08:26.860
oops, sorry, one second.

00:08:26.860 --> 00:08:29.320
Play in their village
to the star pitcher

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:33.620
that led the Red Sox to win
the World Series in 2004,

00:08:33.620 --> 00:08:35.730
Tavares gives us a
beautiful portrait

00:08:35.730 --> 00:08:38.880
of baseball's most prized
and beloved players.

00:08:38.880 --> 00:08:41.860
Growing up Pedro is also
available in Spanish,

00:08:41.860 --> 00:08:45.040
making it even more
accessible to our readers.

00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:48.560
Our second honor title is
another marvelous nonfiction

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:51.770
picture book, Funny
Bones: Posada and His Day

00:08:51.770 --> 00:08:56.350
of the Dead Calaveras by author
and Illustrator Duncan Tonatiuh.

00:08:56.350 --> 00:08:59.140
His latest work presents
an extraordinary blend

00:08:59.140 --> 00:09:02.890
of biography, art and
politics, focusing on the life

00:09:02.890 --> 00:09:05.350
of Jose Guadalupe
Posada or Don Lupe,

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:07.690
as he was known at the time.

00:09:07.690 --> 00:09:11.600
Born in 1852, Posada
was most famous

00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:14.840
for his socially conscious
depictions of calaveras,

00:09:14.840 --> 00:09:18.290
the often comical skeletons that
are associated with Mexico's Day

00:09:18.290 --> 00:09:20.280
of the Dead celebrations.

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:23.720
With Tonatiuh's engaging
hand-drawn digitally collaged

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:27.060
artwork, we first see
Don Lupe as a child

00:09:27.060 --> 00:09:29.190
with a natural talent
for drawing.

00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:30.670
And then as an adult,

00:09:30.670 --> 00:09:34.590
continuously pursuing his
artistic passion while offering

00:09:34.590 --> 00:09:37.290
social commentary on
the world around him.

00:09:37.290 --> 00:09:38.970
The full-page spreads inspired

00:09:38.970 --> 00:09:42.070
by Don Lupe's work
actively probe the reader

00:09:42.070 --> 00:09:46.410
to consider the deeper layers
of meaning behind his artwork,

00:09:46.410 --> 00:09:48.830
such as critiques
about social class,

00:09:48.830 --> 00:09:50.470
rapidly changing technology

00:09:50.470 --> 00:09:53.230
and violence during
the Mexican Revolution.

00:09:53.230 --> 00:09:56.050
This stunning work is
easily adapted to a variety

00:09:56.050 --> 00:09:59.560
of classroom settings, spanning
subject areas such as art,

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:01.790
history and cultural studies.

00:10:01.790 --> 00:10:06.190
Additionally, Tonatiuh includes
a detailed author's note,

00:10:06.190 --> 00:10:08.270
glossary of terms
and a bibliography

00:10:08.270 --> 00:10:12.040
for readers interested in diving
further into Posada's work.

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:14.560
Funny Bones is geared for
readers between grades three

00:10:14.560 --> 00:10:17.330
to six, but older
students, including adults,

00:10:17.330 --> 00:10:19.630
are sure to learn
much from it as well.

00:10:19.630 --> 00:10:21.670
We hope you enjoy this
title, along with all

00:10:21.670 --> 00:10:25.620
of the other wonderful commended
and honor books on our list.

